-------------------------- Document Ingestion and Indexing ----------------------------------------

01) Error Check in file/directory attributes 
02) Stream raw text chunks
03) Normalize text incrementally
04) Enrich chunk metadata
05) Split into semantic sub-chunks
06) Generate embeddings (batched)
07) Store embeddings in vector store

Files --> [01 Validate] --> [02 Stream Raw]  --> [03 Norm Buffer] --> [04 Enrich] 
      --> [05 Split]    --> [06 Embed Batch] --> [07 Store]


------------------------------- Query and Answer Generation Pipeline -------------------------------------

01) Receive user query
02) Normalize / preprocess query
03) Generate embedding for query
04) Retrieve top-K relevant chunks
05) Assemble context from retrieved chunks
06) Build prompt (context + question)
07) Call LLM
08) Post-process LLM response
09) Return final answer (optionally with sources)

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


The pipeline is designed around normalized-text–based chunking, streaming execution, and incremental enrichment. Memory safety, embedding quality, and long-term maintainability are prioritized over convenience. Normalized file copies are supported when necessary but are not imposed as a default constraint.

Normalization is treated as a logical transformation. Normalized text may be materialized to disk when required, but it is not mandatory by default. Allows streaming pipelines to remain memory-safe. One approach is to normalize the entire file and save it as a separate copy before chunking. While effective, this doubles storage and increases I/O overhead.

The system may optionally create a fully normalized copy of a file and chunk from that copy. Certain document types (OCR-heavy PDFs, noisy scans) benefit significantly from full normalization before chunking.

Text is read incrementally, normalized incrementally, and accumulated in a rolling normalized buffer. A chunk is emitted only when the normalized buffer reaches the desired size. Normalizing entire files upfront can be expensive, while chunking raw text first leads to poor semantic chunks.

Chunk boundaries are determined only after text has been normalized. Raw text must never be used to decide chunk size. Extracting fixed-size text segments from unnormalized content can produce chunks dominated by whitespace, OCR artifacts, or invalid symbols. Normalizing such chunks afterward can dramatically shrink them and destroy semantic meaning, resulting in poor-quality embeddings.

The smallest unit of processing in the pipeline is a chunk, not a file or a document. Processing entire files or documents as a single unit fails for large inputs. Memory usage must never scale with file size.

File-level and document-level entities store metadata only (path, size, identifiers, source). Text content exists only transiently at the chunk level. No class or structure is required to hold an entire document’s text in memory.

Each chunk carries sufficient metadata to uniquely identify its source, position, normalization version, and embedding model. Vector databases require rich metadata for filtering, re-indexing, and model migration.

Each stage adds new information (normalized text, chunk metadata, embeddings) rather than destructively replacing earlier data. Overwriting data at each stage makes debugging difficult and prevents partial recovery after failures.

The pipeline must operate correctly with a batch size of one. Batching is treated strictly as an optional optimization. Batch size can be tuned based on environment and API constraints. Core correctness must never depend on batching. This avoids memory-heavy designs and simplifies portability.



The system must support chunk-level resume semantics. Transient failures are expected in large-scale ingestion pipelines. The system must be able to resume from the last successfully processed chunk. Reprocessing entire files due to minor failures is unacceptable.

This Design, rejected file-centric processing, identified normalization as a boundary-defining operation, enforced chunk-level atomicity, and designed for failure, scale, and re-indexing from day one.









